commentBody:
@Man and 2 dogs 

"Trying too hard to be clever" is a *really* common complaint--one that I have never understood.

I think it means, what *I've* meant when I've used "trying too hard", is that you proved you're more clever than I am, and I don't like that a bit.

@Bethh 
Srsly?

Next you'll claim there are hidden emus.

@Mike
That one was perfectly divan!


Are the emus from Davenport, IA?

@Steve 

Yeah, I blanked out on that one. Must have been the foreigner in me?








An emu zips past the LA Maze.

@Rahul 

People who can't distinguish between etymology and entomology bug me in ways I can not put into words.




Emus are definitely not bugs, but they can be very annoying.

@Lewis

My exact experience and sentiment.

The whole solve (including unnecessary prepositions) was a joy, and I'm giddy at the possibility of eight more like it.

@David Connell

I held off on entering Chunk on the first pass, and thought of a new one each time I came back to it.

Great clue for a Saturday!

@Barbara Prillaman 
This almost equaled my worst ever Saturday, which needed 26 cheats.  This one needed 24 cheats.  Sometimes a cheat-heavy puzzle can still be fun.  This wasn't one, for me.  I imagine, however, the 'brainiacs' will be in their element on this one.

Yes, I have hopes for an engrossing Sunday puzzle!

@Helen Wright 

We watched the first two seasons of “Slow Horses” and loved it, but when the price of AppleTV+ almost doubled, we dropped the service. 

My husband got a new iPad in August and Apple offered a free three-month subscription, so we just finished season three of “Slow Horses.” The season four premiere has me really impatient about wanting to see the next episode and figure out what the heck is going on.

@Helen Wright Love the series and adore the books.
Jackson Lamb is, somewhat unbelievably, even more hilariously odious in print.
Mick Herron is one of those authors I wish would “write faster”.

@Nancy 
It's DONGLE, which I knew as something related to computers, but don't ask me what.  And also had to change Meh to MID. I took MID to be short for MIDdling. 
The idea of a SUMORINk is amusing.

@Katie 

I hope you feel better soon. 

I find that my mood strongly affects how I feel about a puzzle. Sometimes I finish one that I didn’t much enjoy and think that I should have saved it for later.

@CaptainQuahog 

It's just fascinating to me that a word like "dongle" can be so universally misinterpreted.  I had exactly the same reaction when I first heard it.

I still giggle inwardly about it.

@Joya 

Yes! 

I'm with you on that.

@JPT 

I agree with everything you said. 

I thought that pod race in “The Phantom Menace” was never going to end.

@Pax Ahimsa Gethen 

I had a similar problem only with Chewy at 30D, which I read as Chevy competitor. 

Way too long before I realized my error.

@Calhouri

Same same! I had insectS for 13A for a long time, till I realized that entry was getting in my way, and then I was all D'OHH! I do that with 'etymology' and 'entomology' if I don't take a second and squint and think. At least I have 'etiology' distinct from those two (I think).

I too had Meh at first at 35A, but even as I filled it in I thought "Hmmm? 'Modern'?", and MID made sense once the SE started filling in.

@Shrike 

What is the plural of uptake?

Or is it that you don't think "uptake" ever needs a plural?

@Laura 

I think that's what comes from years of experience--the ability to figure out which of the cryptic ones are certain enough for you to put your weight on.

I'm not there yet.

@CHC AVL

For a Wednesday or Thursday, sure. But for a Saturday, 50%-harder-than-midweek-puzzles is actually the ticket. So "too clever by half" is perfect for a Saturday!

I loved this puzzle. For me it filled in slowly and gradually, like a flock of blackbirds flitting onto branches of a tree one by one.

@Steve L 
I was actually thinking the other day that we haven't seen a new 'stanza' in quite some time.  The metapuzzle? I think it's the grid alone. At least that's the approach I've been taking each time a new one comes out. Each of the thirteen puzzles will have the same grid.  Grid=blackbird. 

Maybe it's deeper than that, but I'm enjoying the puzzles too much to try to attribute deeper meaning. So we're on the same page, I think.

@Eric Hougland - the kid Anakin was soooo much more annoying than Darth Vader!

That episode was pure trash - oops, so was the next one - oops, and the one after that -

oops, and the five after that -
